Set up

using <- function(...) {
    libs <- unlist(list(...))
    need <- libs <- libs[!unlist(lapply(libs, require, character.only = T))]
    if(length(need) > 0){ 
        install.packages(need, repos = "https://cloud.r-project.org")
        need <- need[!unlist(lapply(need, require, character.only = T))]
        if (length(need) > 0) {
          if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = T))
            install.packages("BiocManager")
          BiocManager::install(need)
        }
    }
    lapply(libs, require, character.only = T)
}

Differential analysis

Lets begin with a simple differential accessibility analysis. While usually one would use raw counts combined with frameworks such as DiffBind that we used in the last lecture (which uses DESeq2/edgeR under the hood), for the sake of simplicity well directly apply t-tests to the normalized and log-transformed enrichment values

T-tests

We now apply a simple T-test to every single peak

This may take a while to run, so you can skip it in class, as the output is included in the RData file 

# set up parallelization
plan(multisession(workers = 24)) # adjust this based on how many cores you have / want to use

# progress bar
handlers(global = TRUE)
handlers("progress")

# sample grouping
escc.idx <- which(esca.rse$primary_diagnosis == "Squamous cell carcinoma, NOS")
esad.idx <- which(esca.rse$primary_diagnosis == "Adenocarcinoma, NOS")

# tests
with_progress({
  p <- progressor(steps = length(esca.rse))
  result <- future_apply(assay(esca.rse), 1, function(peak) {
    p()
    t.test(peak[escc.idx], peak[esad.idx], conf.level = TRUE) %>%
      {c(raw_p_value = .$p.value,
         ESCC_minus_ESAD = .$estimate[1] - .$estimate[2])}
  }) %>% t() %>% as_tibble() %>% mutate(FDR = p.adjust(raw_p_value, method = 'fdr'))
})
raw_p_value ESCC_minus_ESAD FDR

Results

The results can be visualized as weve done for differential gene expression

d <- result %>%
  dplyr::rename(x = ESCC_minus_ESAD, y = raw_p_value) %>%
  mutate(kind = case_when(abs(x) > 2 & y < .01 ~ 'DB',
                          abs(x) > 2 ~ 'big',
                          y < .01 ~ 'sig',
                          T ~ 'NS'),
         y = -log10(y))
ct <- na.omit(d) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(kind == 'DB') %>%
  mutate(up = x > 0) %>%
  dplyr::count(up) %>%
  mutate(x = ifelse(up, Inf, -Inf),
         y = Inf,
         h = as.numeric(up))
ggplot(d, aes(x, y, color = kind)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-2, 2), linetype = 'dashed') +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 2, linetype = 'dashed') +
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  geom_label(aes(x = x, y = y, label = n, hjust = h),
             vjust = 1, data = ct, inherit.aes = F) +
  scale_y_continuous() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c('forestgreen', 'red2', 'grey30',  'royalblue')) +
  labs(x = 'ESCC - ESAD', y = '-log10(p-value)', title = 'Esophageal carcinoma subtypes')

Multi-omics integration

While the ATAC-seq dataset by itself is quite rich, combining it with expression data can yield further insights

Merging

Well need to take a few steps before combining the two modalities

Construct object

While the RNA-seq data already comes in a RangedSummarizedExperiment, well have to again create one for the ATAC-seq data

# make object
esca.peaks.se <- esca.peaks %>% 
  dplyr::select(-c("score", "name")) %>%
  makeSummarizedExperimentFromDataFrame()
rowRanges(esca.peaks.se)$score <- esca.peaks$score
rowRanges(esca.peaks.se)$name <- esca.peaks$name

# rename samples
colnames(esca.peaks.se) <- colnames(esca.peaks.se) %>%

Correlation

For the sake of time, well just look at the shortest chromosome 21

# expression matrix
em <- log2(assay(mae, 'RNA') + 1)
gs <- genes(TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene, filter = list(tx_chrom = 'chr21'))
gs$symbol <- mapIds(org.Hs.eg.db, gs$gene_id, "SYMBOL", "ENTREZID")
gs <- gs[gs$symbol %in% rownames(em)]
em <- em[gs$symbol,]

# accessibility matrix
am <- assay(mae, 'ATAC')
rownames(am) <- rowRanges(mae[['ATAC']]) %>% 
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate(idx = sprintf('%s:%d-%d', seqnames, start, end)) %>%
  pull(idx)
am <- am[grep('chr21', rownames(am)),]

Likewise, well limit ourselves to open sites within 10-100kb of the TSS

  1. Is that a reasonable range to assess cis-regulatory events? What is the typical distance between enhancers and promoters?
# range to look at
hi <- 1e6
lo <- 1e4

# define upstream and downstream regions to check for overlap
up <- dn <- tss <- promoters(gs, upstream = 1, downstream = 0)
start(up) <- start(up) - hi
end(up) <- end(up) - lo

end(dn) <- end(dn) + hi
start(dn) <- start(dn) + lo

# peak coordinates
pks <- tibble(idx = rownames(am)) %>% 
  separate(idx, c('chr', 'start', 'end'), '[:-]') %>%
  makeGRangesFromDataFrame()

# overlap and correlate
res <- list(up, dn) %>%
  lapply(function(x) {
    x <- trim(x)
    findOverlaps(x, pks) %>%
      as.data.frame() %>%
      group_by(queryHits, subjectHits) %>%
      do(cor.test(em[.$queryHits,], am[.$subjectHits,]) %>%
           {data.frame(p = .$p.value, r = .$estimate)})
  }) %>%
  bind_rows() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  mutate(gene = rownames(em)[queryHits],
         tss = start(tss)[queryHits],
         peak = rownames(am)[subjectHits],
         mid = mid(pks)[subjectHits],
         sep = abs(mid - tss),
         FDR = p.adjust(p, method = 'fdr'))

# plot
ggplot(res, aes(x = sep, y = -log10(FDR))) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = r), size = .5, alpha = .5) + 
  scale_color_distiller(type = 'div', limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  geom_smooth() + 
  scale_x_log10()

  1. What is the farthest hit with \(\text{FDR} < 0.01\)? Show the actual expression / accessibility values as a scatter plot and color by condition

Filter links

# create GRanges from links
peak.to.gene.links.merged.gr <- peak.to.gene.links.merged %>%

# colorscale for the accessibility data
pal_atac <- colorRampPalette(c(
  "#053061", "#2166AC", "#4393C3", "#92C5DE", "#D1E5F0",
  "#FDDBC7", "#F4A582", "#D6604D", "#B2182B", "#67001F"
))(100)

# sample annotations
ha = HeatmapAnnotation(
  df = data.frame("Group" = mae$primary_diagnosis),
  show_annotation_name = TRUE,
  col = list(
    Group = c(
      "Squamous cell carcinoma, NOS" =  "red", 
      "Adenocarcinoma, NOS" = "blue"
    )
  ),
  show_legend = TRUE,
  annotation_name_side = "left",
  annotation_name_gp = gpar(fontsize = 6)
)

# z-transform the data for greater visual contrast
atac.mat.row.z.score <- atac.mat %>% t() %>% scale() %>% t()
col.zscore <- colorRamp2(seq(-2, 2, by = 4/99), pal_atac)

# put together actual heatmap
ht_atac <- Heatmap(
  matrix = atac.mat.row.z.score[1:1000,],
  name ="ATAC-seq log2(counts)\nz-score rowwise", 
  col = col.zscore,
  heatmap_legend_param = list(
    legend_width  = unit(3, "cm"),
    legend_direction = "horizontal",
    labels_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12), 
    title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12)
  ),
  show_column_names = FALSE,
  cluster_columns = TRUE,
  show_row_names = FALSE,
  cluster_rows = TRUE, # cluster will be based on ATAC-seq
  row_title = " ATAC-seq peaks",
  top_annotation = ha,
  column_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8),
  row_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 4),
  column_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12), 
  row_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12),
  use_raster = TRUE,
  raster_device = c("png"),
  raster_quality = 2
)

RNA-seq

# colorscale for the expression data
pal_rna <- colorRampPalette(c(
  "#003C30", "#01665E", "#35978F", "#80CDC1", "#C7EAE5",
  "#F6E8C3", "#DFC27D", "#BF812D", "#8C510A", "#543005"
))(100)

# z-transform the data for greater visual contrast
exp.mat.row.z.score <- exp.mat %>% t() %>% scale() %>% t() 
col.zscore <- colorRamp2(seq(-2, 2, by = 4/99), pal_rna)

# sample annotations, basically the same as above except on the other side
ha = HeatmapAnnotation(
  df = data.frame("Group" = mae$primary_diagnosis),
  show_annotation_name = FALSE,
  col = list(
    Group = c(
      "Squamous cell carcinoma, NOS" =  "red", 
      "Adenocarcinoma, NOS" = "blue"
    )
  ),
  show_legend = TRUE,
  annotation_name_side = "right",
  annotation_name_gp = gpar(fontsize = 6)
)

# actual heatmap
ht_exp <- Heatmap(
  matrix = exp.mat.row.z.score[1:1000,],
  name ="RNA-seq FPKM-UQ\nz-score rowwise", 
  col = col.zscore,
  column_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8),
  show_column_names = F,
  heatmap_legend_param = list(
    legend_width  = unit(3, "cm"),
    legend_direction = "horizontal",
    labels_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12), 
    title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12)
  ),
  show_row_names = FALSE,
  cluster_columns = FALSE,
  use_raster = TRUE,
  raster_device = c("png"),
  raster_quality = 2,
  cluster_rows = FALSE, # so we will use the clustering from the other heatmap
  row_title = "RNA-seq linked genes",
  row_title_side = "right",
  column_order = column_order(ht_atac),
  row_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 4),
  top_annotation = ha,
  column_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12), 
  row_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12)
)

Combined

draw(
  object = ht_atac + ht_exp,
  newpage = TRUE, 
  merge_legends = TRUE,
  column_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 12, fontface = "bold"),
  heatmap_legend_side = "bottom",
  annotation_legend_side = "bottom"
)
